      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771499892226,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "dont need the exact timestamp\nwill round the time down to the nearest hour\n=> this will represent the beginning of the hour that that view occured",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "dont need the exact timestamp\nwill round the time down to the nearest hour\n=> this will represent the beginning of the hour that that view occured",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Sn0qgNVd-JH8hr-D5bkcL",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2244.1446811536284,
      "y": 2491.2392693517086,
      "width": 1298.4591064453125,
      "height": 1200,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aV",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1414193056,
      "version": 1905,
      "versionNonce": 705503136,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771499770382,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "failure handling (kafka consumer + kafka producer)\n- we want to make the consumer also aggregate the results over the past hour before storing within the DB\n  => this passes the write heavy operations to the responsibility of the consumer rather than the DB\n  => kafka consumer might fail during this time\n  => resolving this is difficult since require alot of resources to just \"brute force\" catch up and even then, it will be very slow\n        -> kafka retention allows consumer to read data again beginning from the hour BUT\n        -> even if we increase the consumer resources x2, we will process 1 old every second \n\n  => solution: to use checkpointing\n\ncheck pointing/ offsets:\nkafka retention =/= consumer offsets\nkafka retention: keeps old data for 24 hours, deletes old mesages after that => has NTH to do with whether u processed it or not\n\noff sets / checkpointing\noffset: where you are in that data\n\nwhy not just write to ViewsDB (postegrsql)?\n- 100k + views per sec\n    - lock contention\n    - WAL pressure (write ahead log)\n    - Disk I/o bottleneck\n- whereas object storage (like S3)\n    - optimized for massive object writes\n    - massive scale\n    - DONT NEED to maintain indexes\n    - DONT NEED to support transactions\n    - DONT NEED to enforce schema\n    - DONT NEED to do row-level updates\n\n- this lets us update the viewsDB only hourly and only need to do so for the bucket (bucket_hour, video_id) while\nstill letting us have massive writes relatively fast to object store every 5 mins\n- protects us from knowing whether we have flushed this batch safely\n\nplain kafka consumer vs flink\n    plain kafka consumer (no framework)\n    - only stores offset, no aggregation stat => does not persist aggregated state\n\n    flink (stateful stream processing)\n    - maintains kafka offsets\n    - operator state\n    - checkpoint snapshots (all aggregation state)\n    * stores all of them together in a durable storage (S3, HDFS, RocksDB backend)\n\nkafka - conveyor belt of data\nconumer - worker sorting data into bins\ndb - warehouse\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "failure handling (kafka consumer + kafka producer)\n- we want to make the consumer also aggregate the results over the past hour before storing within the DB\n  => this passes the write heavy operations to the responsibility of the consumer rather than the DB\n  => kafka consumer might fail during this time\n  => resolving this is difficult since require alot of resources to just \"brute force\" catch up and even then, it will be very slow\n        -> kafka retention allows consumer to read data again beginning from the hour BUT\n        -> even if we increase the consumer resources x2, we will process 1 old every second \n\n  => solution: to use checkpointing\n\ncheck pointing/ offsets:\nkafka retention =/= consumer offsets\nkafka retention: keeps old data for 24 hours, deletes old mesages after that => has NTH to do with whether u processed it or not\n\noff sets / checkpointing\noffset: where you are in that data\n\nwhy not just write to ViewsDB (postegrsql)?\n- 100k + views per sec\n    - lock contention\n    - WAL pressure (write ahead log)\n    - Disk I/o bottleneck\n- whereas object storage (like S3)\n    - optimized for massive object writes\n    - massive scale\n    - DONT NEED to maintain indexes\n    - DONT NEED to support transactions\n    - DONT NEED to enforce schema\n    - DONT NEED to do row-level updates\n\n- this lets us update the viewsDB only hourly and only need to do so for the bucket (bucket_hour, video_id) while\nstill letting us have massive writes relatively fast to object store every 5 mins\n- protects us from knowing whether we have flushed this batch safely\n\nplain kafka consumer vs flink\n    plain kafka consumer (no framework)\n    - only stores offset, no aggregation stat => does not persist aggregated state\n\n    flink (stateful stream processing)\n    - maintains kafka offsets\n    - operator state\n    - checkpoint snapshots (all aggregation state)\n    * stores all of them together in a durable storage (S3, HDFS, RocksDB backend)\n\nkafka - conveyor belt of data\nconumer - worker sorting data into bins\ndb - warehouse\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
