    {
      "id": "GE2CTDP-8TzZQTyS0rprW",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4023.1703554965766,
      "y": 2497.07765812582,
      "width": 875.8394165039062,
      "height": 475,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ab",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1378238368,
      "version": 1928,
      "versionNonce": 600136608,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771499770382,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Redis cache + cron job\n=> overall improves latency of retrieval. but how?\n=> cache layer - helps to relieve repeated operations done by postgresql for the same call\n=> Top K cron service - helps to do precomputation so that the when client calls,\ndata is already ready\n    - and with cache, even if its not ready, it can use the previous result\n\n=> if cron fails, what do we do?\n    => do we want top K service to just make the request to the postgres DB?\n    => NO! this might be worse (since initially, the Top cron service was not that\n                                heavy as it was only making request once every hour)\n    => amplified the laod on the DB dramatically, when it was underloaded prevly\n\n=> what we could do: increase TTL of cache (so it doesnt get invalidated so early)\n    => store the window: {truncated)timestamp}, with truncated timestamp\n    => \n    *might violate some SLAs! => we are not satisfying the 1 min between event\n                                        & when it was calculated\n                                     => but better than crashing the system",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Redis cache + cron job\n=> overall improves latency of retrieval. but how?\n=> cache layer - helps to relieve repeated operations done by postgresql for the same call\n=> Top K cron service - helps to do precomputation so that the when client calls,\ndata is already ready\n    - and with cache, even if its not ready, it can use the previous result\n\n=> if cron fails, what do we do?\n    => do we want top K service to just make the request to the postgres DB?\n    => NO! this might be worse (since initially, the Top cron service was not that\n                                heavy as it was only making request once every hour)\n    => amplified the laod on the DB dramatically, when it was underloaded prevly\n\n=> what we could do: increase TTL of cache (so it doesnt get invalidated so early)\n    => store the window: {truncated)timestamp}, with truncated timestamp\n    => \n    *might violate some SLAs! => we are not satisfying the 1 min between event\n                                        & when it was calculated\n                                     => but better than crashing the system",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "n8rLVbCtKG83zxqjAmHnl",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2671.4138743974663,
      "y": 2000.5641659686653,
      "width": 1368.718994140625,
      "height": 250,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ac",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 663530400,
      "version": 772,
      "versionNonce": 1560282016,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771499796400,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Estimations:\n- to quantify writes on the DB (from the consumer) => QPS\ninterviewer give: 70 bil views/ day\n\n70 bil / 100k secs = 700k views/ sec (number of write to the DB)   => postgres can handle ~10k qps per instance\n\n- to know whether data in DB is becoming too large to handle?\ninterviewer gives number of vids: 4bil videos on the platform\n\n4 bil vids * ( 8bytes videoId + 8 bytes views = 16 bytes) = 64 bil bytes = 64 GB / hour (last hour, day, week) => days would be 24 * 64GB",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Estimations:\n- to quantify writes on the DB (from the consumer) => QPS\ninterviewer give: 70 bil views/ day\n\n70 bil / 100k secs = 700k views/ sec (number of write to the DB)   => postgres can handle ~10k qps per instance\n\n- to know whether data in DB is becoming too large to handle?\ninterviewer gives number of vids: 4bil videos on the platform\n\n4 bil vids * ( 8bytes videoId + 8 bytes views = 16 bytes) = 64 bil bytes = 64 GB / hour (last hour, day, week) => days would be 24 * 64GB",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "N78bm4SB-i-r4qIe_QJqu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -3091.6162764273217,
      "y": 2494.616173525998,
      "width": 715.3795166015625,
      "height": 925,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ad",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2132047456,
      "version": 1444,
      "versionNonce": 1159634528,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771502613084,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "(scaling out for write) partitioning + sharding\n\n=> kafka msgs only videoId + timestamp\n=> partitioned by videoId\n\nthink about how to partition & shard => by videoId\nfor both views topic & view consumer\neach consumer only handles those few videoIds\n\nshard postgresql DB\ncontains video views 10_000 views/ sec\n\nneed to query each of the shard\n=> can just make the same query to each shard\n=> merge that\n=> query trivially scales\n=> 70x faster rather than just a single instance\n\n*this sharding is fine for postgresql since when merging\nwe arent doing very complex queries\n\n\n\nbatch write to DB:\n- we only care about hourly views for the tumbling hour\n- pre aggregating the hourly views in consumer?\n\nkeep a map in Mem of all views received & not yet flushed out to the DB\nevery hour write to the DB\n# of writes are now not bounded by views,\n    but by the # of videos that have views in that hour\nslammed by substantially smaller vol of write queries\n\ntech stack:\n- flink\n\n(failure of consumers now need to be handled)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "(scaling out for write) partitioning + sharding\n\n=> kafka msgs only videoId + timestamp\n=> partitioned by videoId\n\nthink about how to partition & shard => by videoId\nfor both views topic & view consumer\neach consumer only handles those few videoIds\n\nshard postgresql DB\ncontains video views 10_000 views/ sec\n\nneed to query each of the shard\n=> can just make the same query to each shard\n=> merge that\n=> query trivially scales\n=> 70x faster rather than just a single instance\n\n*this sharding is fine for postgresql since when merging\nwe arent doing very complex queries\n\n\n\nbatch write to DB:\n- we only care about hourly views for the tumbling hour\n- pre aggregating the hourly views in consumer?\n\nkeep a map in Mem of all views received & not yet flushed out to the DB\nevery hour write to the DB\n# of writes are now not bounded by views,\n    but by the # of videos that have views in that hour\nslammed by substantially smaller vol of write queries\n\ntech stack:\n- flink\n\n(failure of consumers now need to be handled)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
